{"id": "18233", "revid": "3407035", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=18233", "title": "Auction House", "text": "The Auction House\u00a0was a feature of the PC version of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". This allowed players to put items up for auction, bid and buyout. Two versions of the auction house existed. One used &lt;a href=\"gold\"&gt;gold&lt;/a&gt; earned in-game while the second used real-world currency. Sales and purchases from the Real Money Auction House (RMAH) could be funded by either the players &lt;a href=\"Battle.net\"&gt;Battle.net&lt;/a&gt; account balance or a separate e-commerce service such as PayPal. The Auction House was introduced as a means of combating third-party trading of items. The developers were left with the choice of removing trading, or integrating it into the game economy, thus reducing the incentive to use third parties. According to &lt;a href=\"Jay%20Wilson\"&gt;Jay Wilson&lt;/a&gt; however, after release, it was clear that the Auction House had made getting items too easy. Within two months of the game's launch, he had come to regret implementing the Auction House, but wasn't sure if it should be shut down. While there was a lot of criticism from the playerbase towards the Auction House, the developers had to consider how many were using the service. Contrary to some players' beliefs, Wilson has stated that the Auction House was not pushed on &lt;a href=\"Blizzard%20Entertainment\"&gt;Blizzard&lt;/a&gt; by \"corporate overlords.\"\nThe Auction House's disbandenment was suggested by &lt;a href=\"Josh%20Mosqueira\"&gt;Josh Mosqueira&lt;/a&gt;, who had been brought in as game director. After a short discussion, the entire team, even those on the business side thought it would make the most sense. After this change, it gave the team the ability to make sure to reward players with better items, clear and concise tool tips, and &lt;a href=\"Adventure%20Mode\"&gt;Adventure Mode&lt;/a&gt;. Wilson supported his move, attributing Mosqueira as being the driving force for shutting down the Auction House.\nThe Auction House service was discontinued on March 18, 2014. &lt;a href=\"Blizzard%20Entertainment\"&gt;Blizzard&lt;/a&gt;'s original goal was to provide a convenient and secure system for trades, but it was found that the auction house undermined the game's loot-based gameplay. Subsequently, &lt;a href=\"Loot%202.0\"&gt;Loot 2.0&lt;/a&gt; has been introduced in \"&lt;a href=\"Reaper%20of%20Souls\"&gt;Reaper of Souls&lt;/a&gt;\". Most, if not all, means of player-to-player trade were eliminated in result."}
{"id": "24854", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=24854", "title": "Audacity", "text": "Audacity is a\u00a0\u00a0passive skill, unlocked at level 66.\nIn-game.\nDamage increase is multiplicative to all other modifiers.\nThis ability, predictably, is most useful for melee Wizards.\n&lt;a href=\"Hydra%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Hydra&lt;/a&gt; deals additional damage to enemies within 15 yards of the Wizard, not of itself.\n&lt;a href=\"Power%20Hungry\"&gt;Power Hungry&lt;/a&gt; serves as a direct opposite of this skill."}
{"id": "21793", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=21793", "title": "Aughild", "text": "Aughild was a king of &lt;a href=\"Entsteig\"&gt;Entsteig&lt;/a&gt;.\nBiography.\nAughild was the only warlord to ever successfully besiege &lt;a href=\"Entsteig%20%28City%29\"&gt;Entsteig&lt;/a&gt;. He gave the nobles fifty demands that had to be met before he would spare their lives. Those demands were later written into his &lt;a href=\"Aughild%27s%20Search\"&gt;bracers&lt;/a&gt;. Aughild was crowned king of Entsteig and his &lt;a href=\"Aughild%27s%20Rule\"&gt;vestments&lt;/a&gt; were crafted to reflect both his savagery and his nobility.\nIt is rumored that the grave of Aughild was pillaged by the ghosts of those he slew, and that those ghosts carry shards of his armor with them to this very day.\nIn-game.\nAughild is the namesake of the &lt;a href=\"Aughild%27s%20Victory\"&gt;Aughild's Victory&lt;/a&gt;/&lt;a href=\"Aughild%27s%20Authority\"&gt;Authority&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Set%20Items\"&gt;Set Items&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "26075", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=26075", "title": "Aughild's Authority", "text": "Aughild's Authority\u00a0is a level 70 crafted\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Set%20Items\"&gt;item set&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0in\u00a0\"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nThis set is named for\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Aughild\"&gt;Aughild&lt;/a&gt;, a warlord who conquered and was crowned king of\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Entsteig\"&gt;Entsteig&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe set requires a character level of 70. It can be crafted by the\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Haedrig%20Eamon\"&gt;Blacksmith&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0with the Aughild's Authority plan. Prior to Patch 2.0.6., each piece required one &lt;a href=\"Shard%20of%20Entsteig%20Plate\"&gt;Shard of Entsteig Plate&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe level 42 version of this set is &lt;a href=\"Aughild%27s%20Victory\"&gt;Aughild's Victory&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis set is often used for fresh 70 characters: with a &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20Royal%20Grandeur\"&gt;Ring of Royal Grandeur&lt;/a&gt;, it can be completed with just two items, usually shoulders and bracers. This gives &lt;a href=\"The%20Nephalem\"&gt;the Nephalem&lt;/a&gt; some much needed protection and damage boost, especially against &lt;a href=\"Elite%20Monsters\"&gt;elite monsters&lt;/a&gt;, the likes of which tend to be responsible for \"most\" of the deaths suffered by champions of the Light.\nPieces.\nThe set consists of four items, three of which are required to complete it. All items are completely randomized, with no guaranteed properties.\nSet Bonus:"}
