{"id": "39606", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=39606", "title": "Skeletal Mage (Diablo Immortal)", "text": "The Skeletal Mage is a powerful &lt;a href=\"Skeleton%20Mage\"&gt;Skeleton Mage&lt;/a&gt; raised by &lt;a href=\"Lethes\"&gt;Lethes&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn-game.\nThe Skeletal Mage is a &lt;a href=\"boss\"&gt;boss&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". It is encountered in &lt;a href=\"Queen%20Asylla%27s%20Tomb\"&gt;Queen Asylla's Tomb&lt;/a&gt; during the \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Tomb%20of%20the%20Queen\"&gt;The Tomb of the Queen&lt;/a&gt;\" &lt;a href=\"quest\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Skeletal Mage is immune to &lt;a href=\"knockback\"&gt;knockback&lt;/a&gt;. It has a frontal beam attack, and rotates. It can &lt;a href=\"teleport\"&gt;teleport&lt;/a&gt;, after which it summons green spheres in a line, which chase the player as missiles."}
{"id": "46442", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=46442", "title": "Skeletal Mage (monster)", "text": "Skeletal Mages are a type of &lt;a href=\"undead\"&gt;undead&lt;/a&gt; seen in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". They can cast rudimentary &lt;a href=\"magic\"&gt;magic&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nFew make better targets for unlife than those with the will to work magic. Freed of their bothersome caution, they fling baleful &lt;a href=\"arcane\"&gt;arcana&lt;/a&gt;, heedless of the damage. Summoners compulsively raise &lt;a href=\"skeleton\"&gt;skeleton&lt;/a&gt;s. perpetuating an endless spiral of resurrection that will surely overwhelm humanity one day.\nIn-game.\nThey can be found in &lt;a href=\"Ashwold%20Cemetery\"&gt;Ashwold Cemetery&lt;/a&gt; at &lt;a href=\"the%20Ossuary\"&gt;the Ossuary&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Queen%20Asylla%27s%20Tomb\"&gt;Queen Asylla's Tomb&lt;/a&gt;. They are normally accompanied by &lt;a href=\"Skeletal%20Warrior\"&gt;Skeletal Warrior&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"Skeletal%20Shieldbearer\"&gt;Skeletal Shieldbearer&lt;/a&gt;s. They attack by shooting honing &lt;a href=\"arcane\"&gt;arcane&lt;/a&gt; orbs from their staffs; up to four in succession. Getting hit does damage and has the chance to &lt;a href=\"blind\"&gt;blind&lt;/a&gt; the player.\nEthereal versions of the Skeletal Mage called &lt;a href=\"Spectral%20Sorcerer\"&gt;Spectral Sorcerer&lt;/a&gt;s also feature in Diablo Immortal, though they are only called so within the &lt;a href=\"Mad%20King%27s%20Breach\"&gt;Mad King's Breach&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "35263", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=35263", "title": "Skeletal Mage (skill)", "text": "Skeletal Mage (formerly Raise Dead) is a Secondary skill in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". Unlike its &lt;a href=\"Raise%20Skeletal%20Mage\"&gt;previous incarnation&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\", it serves more as a direct damage spell than a summoning skill.\nIn-game.\nWhen cast, summons a Skeletal Mage for a brief period to attack the designated target (unless it is out of reach, dies, or is unattackable, in which case the skeleton retargets to another random foe, like a normal pet). Throughout the duration, the Mage follows its master.\nThe Necromancer can have a total of 10 Mages at any given time; excess Mages will despawn the previously summoned minions. Mages are summoned right next to the Necromancer. The buff icon displays the duration for the oldest summoned Mage to help keep track on them, while the total number of Mages is displayed at the portrait.\nThe damage in the tooltip does not represent the total damage of the Skeletal Mage, but rather the damage each summoned Mage deals \"per attack\". The number of attacks it can make is only limited by its duration and &lt;a href=\"attack%20speed\"&gt;attack speed&lt;/a&gt;. Each attack consists of two energy bolts released in quick succession, normally dealing 200% damage per bolt.\nDevelopment.\nWhen developing the ability, it seemed straight forward at first, but it took a long time to find its spot in the Necromancer kit. Pets have \"an unspoken cool factor,\" and if they don't immediately feel awesome then it doesn't matter what the pet actually does. Once the team received really cool art from a character artist, it set the tone for the skill. The development period lasted three months."}
{"id": "10404", "revid": "48080954", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=10404", "title": "Skeletal Mage Damage", "text": "Relative Skill Levels.\nTo calculate the Necromages' damage we need to know the Relative Skill Level (RSL) of their missiles. This can be done by looking in the following table. Your &lt;a href=\"Raise%20Skeletal%20Mage\"&gt;Raise Skeletal Mage&lt;/a&gt; level is across the top, your &lt;a href=\"Skeleton%20Mastery\"&gt;Skeleton Mastery&lt;/a&gt; is along the left side. The box that meets up is your Relative Skill Level.\nThe following formula is used to calculate the relative skill level of the missile:\n('Skeleton Mastery'.lvl) + ((lvl &lt; 4)?0:((lvl-2)/2)).\nThis means: to calculate relative skill level we take Skeleton Mastery level as base for the calculation ('Skeleton Mastery'.lvl), than we add (Raise Skeletal Mage Skill Level-2)/2 provided that Raise Skeletal Mage level is equal or above level 4. If it's on level 3 or less we do not add anything ((lvl &lt; 4)?0). \nBenefit Per RSL.\nThis list is to show what your Skeletal Mages gain per Relative Skill Level. The table that follows will list all the damage the Skeletal Mages can do.\nPoison.\nIt gains 10 seconds poison duration per level &lt;br&gt;\n1-8 levels it gains 1 poison damage per level &lt;br&gt; \n9-15 levels it gains 2 poison damage per level &lt;br&gt; \n16-22 levels it gains 4 poison damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n23-29 levels it gains 6 poison damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n30+ levels it gains 8 poison damage per level\nCold.\nIt gains 1 second cold duration per level (norm difficulty) &lt;br&gt;\n1-8 levels it gains 1 cold damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n9-15 levels it gains 2 cold damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n16-22 levels it gains 3 cold damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n23-29 levels it gains 4 cold damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n30+ levels it gains 5 cold damage per level\nFire.\n1-8 levels it gains 2 fire damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n9-15 levels it gains 3 fire damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n16-22 levels it gains 5 fire damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n23-29 levels it gains 7 fire damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n30+ levels it gains 9 fire damage per level\nLightning.\nIt gains 1 minimum lightning damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n1-8 levels it gains 3 max lightning damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n9-15 levels it gains 5 max lightning damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n16-22 levels it gains 8 max lightning damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n23-29 levels it gains 11 max lightning damage per level &lt;br&gt;\n30+ levels it gains 14 max lightning damage per level\nDamage Table.\nBelow is the table of Necromage missile's damage according to the relative skill level listed in the above table. The table only goes to 30 since the numbers after that are standard and should be pretty easy to set up. "}
{"id": "41993", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=41993", "title": "Skeletal Marauder", "text": "The Skeletal Marauder is a type of &lt;a href=\"skeleton\"&gt;skeleton&lt;/a&gt; enemy in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\".\nLore.\nDespite their apparent sluggishness, marauders showcase unnatural speed when near the warmth of the living. They block attacks with a surprising quickness, and lunge forth to deliver crippling overhead strikes, then amble slowly away once their quarry's &lt;a href=\"blood\"&gt;blood&lt;/a&gt; finally runs cold.\nIn-game.\ns are encountered in the &lt;a href=\"Tomb%20of%20Fahir\"&gt;Tomb of Fahir&lt;/a&gt;, and at the &lt;a href=\"Putrid%20Marsh\"&gt;Putrid Marsh&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Bilefen\"&gt;Bilefen&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Marauder is slow-moving, and carries a &lt;a href=\"swords\"&gt;sword&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"shields\"&gt;shield&lt;/a&gt;. With the latter, it can generate a forward-facing shield, making it immune to damage when attacked head-on. It can still be damaged in this state if the player attacks from its rear, however."}
