{"id": "27897", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27897", "title": "Slain Monsters Rest In Peace", "text": ""}
{"id": "18283", "revid": "9305822", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=18283", "title": "Slain Monsters Rest in Peace", "text": " is a special modifier seen on only a few select items. It prevents monsters from being resurrected, either by other monsters or the player character.\nThis effect can be both beneficial and detrimental, depending on circumstances. Enemies such as the &lt;a href=\"Fallen%20Shaman\"&gt;Fallen Shaman&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Mummy\"&gt;Greater Mummy&lt;/a&gt; are made much more vulnerable as they will no longer be able to bring their guardians back to life, however resurrection skills that require the presence of a corpse will also be rendered useless. This can be especially harmful to &lt;a href=\"Necromancer\"&gt;Necromancer&lt;/a&gt;s, who depend on bodies for multiple skills.\nDespite the extreme rarity of this effect on items, it is not particularly valuable, as shattering frozen enemies grants the same basic results and is much easier to accomplish than finding an item with the Slain Monsters Rest in Peace effect.\nMechanics.\nSlain Monsters Rest in Peace will prevent a monster from being able to be resurrected, but it will also destroy the effectiveness of player skills that require a corpse, such as &lt;a href=\"Corpse%20Explosion\"&gt;Corpse Explosion&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Corpse%20Lance\"&gt;Corpse Lance&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Find%20Potion\"&gt;Find Potion&lt;/a&gt;. To take effect, the monster must be killed with &lt;a href=\"physical\"&gt;physical&lt;/a&gt; or elemental &lt;a href=\"damage\"&gt;damage&lt;/a&gt;, \"not\" &lt;a href=\"Arcane\"&gt;magic damage&lt;/a&gt;, however the &lt;a href=\"Paladin\"&gt;Paladin&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"Blessed%20Hammer\"&gt;Blessed Hammer&lt;/a&gt; \"does\" work.\nList.\nThe following is a list of all items with Slain Monsters Rest in Peace:\nDiablo III.\nIn Diablo III, with the introduction of a &lt;a href=\"Critical%20Hit\"&gt;Critical Hit&lt;/a&gt; mechanic, the value of this attribute decreased. However, as a reference towards the original Diablo II property, a new attribute was added: Slain enemies rest in\u00a0\"pieces\", a pun often used in popular culture.\nThis adds a Critical Hit-like destruction of enemy &lt;a href=\"corpse\"&gt;corpse&lt;/a&gt; to every attack. Note that on &lt;a href=\"Torment%20%28difficulty%29\"&gt;Torment difficulty&lt;/a&gt;, the presence of resurrectors (like s or &lt;a href=\"Flesh%20Shaman\"&gt;Flesh Shaman&lt;/a&gt;s) does not allow the corpses to be destroyed by any means other than Critical Hits. Also remember that monsters that explode on death (&lt;a href=\"Accursed\"&gt;Accursed&lt;/a&gt; or s, to name a few) will still do so; there is no way to prevent their final attempt at revenge.\nAll &lt;a href=\"Holy%20damage\"&gt;Holy damage&lt;/a&gt; skills and &lt;a href=\"skill%20runes\"&gt;skill runes&lt;/a&gt; destroy corpses of enemies they kill, effectively having this property as a free trait. The only classes utilizing this damage type are &lt;a href=\"Crusader\"&gt;Crusader&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Monk\"&gt;Monk&lt;/a&gt;, though.\nThese effects only destroy corpses that monsters can use: secondary resource of s, the corpses only visible to them, remain intact. This includes the Necromancers' own attacks, so they don't leave themselves without fresh bodies with their own critical blows."}
