{"id": "52137", "revid": "44564686", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=52137", "title": "Server Merge", "text": "A server merge is a rare event in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\" where multiple servers are merged into one.\nEffects.\nEven if several servers are merged into one, the old server names still appear in the server list. A globe icon appears next to the server name, and clicking on this icon displays a list of the other servers that have been merged with it. Characters are still tagged to one of the original servers and can only be accessed by selecting that particular server, but after logging in, they will see the same players on the server. This means the same account can hold not just 5 characters per server but 5 times the number of servers merged into one. The set of servers that have been merged is informally referred to as a \"server cluster\".\nNames.\nIt is possible that after the merge, two players, clans or &lt;a href=\"warband\"&gt;warband&lt;/a&gt;s with the same end up on the same server. If this happens, they are renamed to a name suffixed with a dash and a number (so e.g. Player becomes Player-1). The name can be changed afterwards. Note that a dash is not a valid character in player names, so having a name with a dash may be perceived as a limited-edition cosmetic.\nAccursed Towers.\n&lt;a href=\"Accursed%20Towers\"&gt;Accursed Towers&lt;/a&gt; are affected by the server merge, since the same tower might be occupied by a different clan on a different server. To keep things fair, all Accursed Towers are reset to no owner after the merge. The season number is reset to 1. The season start date is updated to the date of the server merge, but the end date is not changed. There is no compensation for the lost towers other than the unclaimed rewards being sent out. Therefore it is advised to max out the reward chests on any towers owned at the start of the week of the merge.\nLeader Boards.\nAll leader boards are re-ranked with all the players from the merged servers. The first clear leader boards for &lt;a href=\"Challenge%20Rift\"&gt;Challenge Rift&lt;/a&gt; will display all the first clears from every server, but still only one reward can be claimed per 10 levels no matter how many players are listed.\nShadows.\nCharacters and clans retain their &lt;a href=\"Shadow\"&gt;Shadow&lt;/a&gt; status, Marks and Shadow task progress through the merge. &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20War\"&gt;Shadow War&lt;/a&gt; is skipped during a week of the merge - the sign up button does not work, and the brackets will be empty. The \"Top 10\" page will display no clans for the rest of the week after the merge.\nBecause of the re-ranking, clans that were in Class A before the merge can find themselves downgraded to Class C. If there are not enough weeks left in the reign, they may be unable to regain their Class A standing and participate in the &lt;a href=\"Rite%20of%20Exile\"&gt;Rite of Exile&lt;/a&gt; to get a chance at winning the next reign.\nImmortals.\nSince there can be only one alliance of &lt;a href=\"Immortals\"&gt;Immortals&lt;/a&gt; after the merge, the alliance with the highest dominance is chosen to be the Immortals after the merge. All other clans who were Immortals are reverted to &lt;a href=\"Adventurers\"&gt;Adventurers&lt;/a&gt;.\nCycle of Strife.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Cycle%20of%20Strife\"&gt;Cycle of Strife&lt;/a&gt; counter is set to the length of the reign of the Immortal alliance that was chosen to be the Immortals on the merged server. The Cycle of Strife event on Sunday evening is skipped, including the prediction challenges. At the start of the next week, the reign counter increases, unless it was already at 7/7, in which case it stays the same.\nIf there was a reign change on the last Sunday before the merge, the Cycle's Turn daily rewards and the &lt;a href=\"Cycle%27s%20Turn%20Chest\"&gt;Cycle's Turn Chest&lt;/a&gt; option from the &lt;a href=\"Hilts\"&gt;Hilts&lt;/a&gt; vendor are cancelled before their regular end date.\n&lt;a href=\"Deeds%20of%20Valor\"&gt;Deeds of Valor&lt;/a&gt; scores are set to the maximum for all players as part of the merge.\nCompensation.\nA compensation mail with 3 &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Crest\"&gt;Legendary Crest&lt;/a&gt;s and one &lt;a href=\"Normal%20Gems\"&gt;Normal Gem&lt;/a&gt; of every type is sent out.\nFestival of Dawn.\n&lt;a href=\"Festival%20of%20Dawn\"&gt;Festival of Dawn&lt;/a&gt; runs for 11 days after the server merge, although the actual start may be delayed.\nHistory.\nA large number of servers was merged on June 26, 2024."}
{"id": "52138", "revid": "2011810", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=52138", "title": "Server merge", "text": ""}
{"id": "21", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=21", "title": "Sescheron", "text": "Sescheron was the capital of the s, prior to its fall to the &lt;a href=\"Army%20of%20Destruction\"&gt;Army of Destruction&lt;/a&gt;. It is located roughly to the south of &lt;a href=\"Harrogath\"&gt;Harrogath&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nSescheron was an extraordinarily large city; a living symbol of united Barbarian tribes. Its gates guarded the lone path to the &lt;a href=\"Worldstone\"&gt;Worldstone&lt;/a&gt;, and the Children of Bul-Kathos were tasked with defending them. It was believed that the city would never fall, and the people of the &lt;a href=\"Northern%20Steppes\"&gt;Northern Steppes&lt;/a&gt; would always stand vigilant.\nHistory.\nThe Day All Hope Was Lost.\nBy the time of the city's fall, the Barbarians had guarded Sescheron for countless generations. In its last days, it was ruled by Chief Elder &lt;a href=\"Kanai\"&gt;Kanai&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231265\"&gt;1265&lt;/a&gt;, Sescheron was besieged by the &lt;a href=\"Prime%20Evil\"&gt;Prime Evil&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Baal\"&gt;Baal&lt;/a&gt; and his &lt;a href=\"Army%20of%20Destruction\"&gt;Army of Destruction&lt;/a&gt; during their assault on Mount Arreat. Barbarians from various tribes were present at the city during the siege. Baal was greeted by a lone emissary who demanded that Baal and his forces withdraw, and that the Worldstone would never be his. Infuriated, Baal summoned demonic forces to tear the emissary apart, before letting loose his forces upon the city. Baal had drawn first &lt;a href=\"blood\"&gt;blood&lt;/a&gt;, but in what would be called \"the day all hope was lost,\" far more blood would be spilt.\nChief Elder Kanai and his people stood their ground against the impossible flood of Baal\u2019s army with every fiber of their being. However, the defenses were overcome and the city was sacked over the course of a single day. There were only a few survivors, and they described Baal as remaining atop his litter, surveying the city with ravenous malice and an insatiable lust for destruction. With Sescheron having fallen, Baal's forces marched on &lt;a href=\"Harrogath\"&gt;Harrogath&lt;/a&gt;, leaving Sescheron in ruins, along with the hopeless madness of a failed people, and the cold, empty shadows of a once mighty civilization.\nThe Ruins of Sescheron.\n&lt;a href=\"Timeline%231270\"&gt;Five years&lt;/a&gt; after its fall, Sescheron lay infested by &lt;a href=\"Baal%27s%20Minion\"&gt;Baal's Minion&lt;/a&gt;s and other demons. With the opening of the &lt;a href=\"Hell%20Portal\"&gt;Hell Gate&lt;/a&gt;, demons from Hell had clear access to &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;, and began moving into the mortal realm, moving against &lt;a href=\"Bitter%20Hearth\"&gt;Bitter Hearth&lt;/a&gt;. The Barbarians there requested aid from &lt;a href=\"adventurer\"&gt;adventurer&lt;/a&gt;s to thin out the demons before they reached the village.\n&lt;a href=\"Timeline%231285\"&gt;Twenty years&lt;/a&gt; after its fall, Sescheron lay empty, standing in a frozen wasteland. The Hell Gate that had been opened 15 years prior had apparently closed by this point. &lt;a href=\"Monster\"&gt;Monster&lt;/a&gt;s came up from the forests and down from the mountains to infest its ruins. Months after the defeat of &lt;a href=\"Malthael\"&gt;Malthael&lt;/a&gt;, the ruins were explored by &lt;a href=\"the%20Nephalem\"&gt;the Nephalem&lt;/a&gt; and the spirit of &lt;a href=\"Zoltun%20Kulle\"&gt;Zoltun Kulle&lt;/a&gt;, as they sought to recover a &lt;a href=\"Kanai%27s%20Cube\"&gt;Barbarian artifact&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe city ruins are now a dangerous place, infested to the core with &lt;a href=\"khazra\"&gt;khazra&lt;/a&gt;, lost demons and all kinds of beasts. However, they all pale in comparison with &lt;a href=\"the%20Unclean\"&gt;the Unclean&lt;/a&gt;, survivors of the Siege driven mad by Worldstone's destruction. Now a tribe of vicious cannibals, they are the only inhabitants of the ruined city. Other Barbarians spent years trying to rid the Ruins of Sescheron of both vermin and flesh-eaters, but with little to no success.\nIn-game.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Ruins%20of%20Sescheron\"&gt;Ruins of Sescheron&lt;/a&gt; are available in the &lt;a href=\"Adventure%20Mode\"&gt;Adventure Mode&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\" as of patch 2.3.0. Specifically in , near the &lt;a href=\"Arreat%20Crater\"&gt;Arreat Crater&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "29256", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29256", "title": "Set", "text": ""}
{"id": "32724", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32724", "title": "Set Dungeon", "text": "Set Dungeons are a feature in &lt;a href=\"Adventure%20Mode\"&gt;Adventure Mode&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", introduced in patch 2.4.\nOverview.\nSet Dungeons are designed for players at near peak performance with their armor &lt;a href=\"set\"&gt;set&lt;/a&gt; bonuses. These dungeons revolve around set bonuses for specific 6 piece armor sets. They \"can\" be completed while in a group, but only the dungeon creator needs to wear the set, and only they will get the completion and credit for the objectives (still, however, other players may support them with extra kills and buffs). Monsters within drop no loot (but still grant &lt;a href=\"experience\"&gt;experience&lt;/a&gt;).\nEach Set Dungeon has three normal objectives and one mastery objective.\nThe goal is to complete the \"first\" (kill the specified number of enemies without dying) objective, and at least one of the two (\"second\" and/or \"third\") in one run. Mastery rating is optional, and requires killing all enemies, and completion of \"all\" objectives within the time limit (Mastery objective). Most objectives display tips when attempted: for instance, if one needs to hit a certain number of enemies with a single cast, a number of enemies hit will be displayed each time.\nSet Dungeons are not randomized: they always have same layout, enemies, tasks etc. There will be a large (hundreds) amount of regular monsters of fixed types, and several identical &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Monsters\"&gt;Unique Monsters&lt;/a&gt; (always of same type), who will have fixed affixes. However, Elites spawn at random positions each time (unless stated otherwise). Originally, there was also an idea of a boss spawning at the end of each dungeon, designed to 'test' the set the player has acquired, but that idea was scrapped.\nThere are four dungeons per &lt;a href=\"class\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; (total of 24, plus 4 more for s): &lt;a href=\"Patterns%20of%20Justice\"&gt;Patterns of Justice&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Aegis%20of%20Valor\"&gt;Aegis of Valor&lt;/a&gt; do not have their dedicated dungeons. If a player completes the objectives for each of a class's four dungeons, they will receive a special &lt;a href=\"Ascendant%20Pennants\"&gt;class pennant&lt;/a&gt; reflecting their achievement, and &lt;a href=\"Mastery%20Pennants\"&gt;another pennant&lt;/a&gt; for completing them all with Mastery rating. If all 24 dungeons of classes except Necromancers are completed, special wings will be received: &lt;a href=\"Wings%20of%20the%20Dedicated\"&gt;Wings of the Dedicated&lt;/a&gt;. If the 24 dungeons are completed with Mastery rating, another set of wings will be received: &lt;a href=\"Wings%20of%20Mastery\"&gt;Wings of Mastery&lt;/a&gt;. Also, a &lt;a href=\"Banner\"&gt;Banner&lt;/a&gt; Sigil is granted for each of the 28 dungeons regardless of rating.\nA player needs to have the set bonus active for all 6 items to enter the dungeon. With &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20Royal%20Grandeur\"&gt;Ring of Royal Grandeur&lt;/a&gt;, it drops the requirement to 5 pieces of the same set to enter a dungeon.\nPlayers cannot die in a Set Dungeon, but are forced to restart should they lose all Life or fail both second and third objectives. As of 2.6.0, the easiest way to restart the dungeon, to avoid dying or moving all the way to the entrance, is to use &lt;a href=\"Town%20Portal\"&gt;Town Portal&lt;/a&gt;, which is not interrupted by damage in Set Dungeons, and then take a portal back.\nSet Dungeons are scattered across the world, their locations hinted at in the Leoric's Library of &lt;a href=\"Royal%20Quarters\"&gt;Royal Quarters&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Elite%20Monsters\"&gt;Elite Monsters&lt;/a&gt; in Set Dungeons periodically drop lore entries on the dungeons' nature. If player enters the Library wearing a set of 6+ items, they will find a lore book with hints to finding their current set dungeon.\nSet Dungeon difficulty is static (somewhere near T4 or T5), and cannot be changed. The current difficulty setting has no effect on it. However, most objectives are specifically designed in a way so that game difficulty has minimal impact on the difficulty of their completion.\nSome &lt;a href=\"Legendary\"&gt;Legendary&lt;/a&gt; or Set items make Set Dungeon objectives much easier or even trivialize them. However, one must be wary that certain objectives require player to complete a specific action without killing foes prematurely, therefore too powerful gear may sometimes be a disadvantage. Unequipping or changing items and even skills can solve these issues if need arises. However, one cannot change skills and/or gear while within the dungeon, so this must be done in advance.\nAs of patch 2.6.0, all monsters within Set Dungeons are highlighted on the map from the start.\nSet Portals.\nPortals to Set Dungeons are hidden in fixed locations (see details below). A transparent silhouette of an obelisk is barely visible, materializing as player approaches. A portal opens when one comes next to an obelisk. The obelisks will only appear and allow entrance if the character is wearing a complete matching set.\nList of Set Dungeons.\n&lt;a href=\"Monk\"&gt;Monk&lt;/a&gt;.\n&lt;a href=\"Raiment%20of%20a%20Thousand%20Storms\"&gt;Raiment of a Thousand Storms&lt;/a&gt;.\n\"Note\": &lt;a href=\"Pylons\"&gt;Speed Pylons&lt;/a&gt; appear in this dungeon\nMastery Walkthrough.\nBeating all 28 Set Dungeons is very easy if one goes for just one objective, but for Mastery rating, some effort is required. See the guides page for more information.\nDevelopment.\nThe idea for Set Dungeons originated from a \"game jam\" session in 2015. The key idea was that it would be something extra for a completed set, with one dungeon per set, with a hidden entrance somewhere in the world. When a set was completed, a &lt;a href=\"tome\"&gt;tome&lt;/a&gt; would appear at the player's feet, providing a hint as to where the entrance to the dungeon was.\n&lt;a href=\"Alex%20Sulman\"&gt;Alex Sulman&lt;/a&gt; was the lead designer for the Set Dungeon project. Sulman dwelled on the idea for a long time before implementing it; little iteration of the original concept was carried out. Originally, Set Dungeons were designed as an exclusively solo experience. If a player died in the dungeon or left it, the dungeon would reset. A problem was run into with the console version, as players play on the same screen, so one player couldn't enter a Set Dungeon by themselves. The system was altered to have a primary player (the \"dungeon owner\") within a Set Dungeon, and let other players join in to help. The Set Dungeon code had to be rewritten to factor in multiplayer.\nLeaderboards were considered for Set Dungeons, but were not implemented. It was believed that as a Leaderboard filled up, new players would be discouraged from participating.\nThe Delsere's Magnum Opus dungeon was the first one designed. Some dungeons were easier to design than others. For instance, the Thorns of the Invoker dungeon underwent a full rework. &lt;a href=\"Wyatt%20Cheng\"&gt;Wyatt Cheng&lt;/a&gt; worked with Sullman on defining the dungeon's objectives. However, the Barbarian dungeons were easily designed. The Shadow's Mantle dungeon was another early dungeon designed."}
