{"id": "48379", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48379", "title": "Shardborne", "text": "The Shardborne are grotesque &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;ic beings created from &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;people&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"animal\"&gt;animal&lt;/a&gt;s infused with shards of the corrupted &lt;a href=\"Worldstone\"&gt;Worldstone&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nA human/animal may become a Shardborne if their flesh is pierced by a Worldstone shard. This initiates decay that results in a twisted amalgamation of flesh. The warping progress can take time (potentially weeks), and the unlucky soul can fall ill, tormented by maddening visions and voices bound in agony. The formerly deceased may also be turned into Shardborne, and similarly, the transformation can kill the unlucky soul, and subsequently resurrect them. Organic matter can also be turned into a Shardborne.\nThe transformation may be halted, or in its late stages kept at bay, by exposure to &lt;a href=\"Light\"&gt;Light&lt;/a&gt;. However, one's inner light cannot stop the transformation. This might be due to the curse &lt;a href=\"Baal\"&gt;Baal&lt;/a&gt; placed on the Worldstone (to bleed the light of humanity away, thereby turning them into demons).\nPeople who were scratched, not pierced, by splinters of the Worldstone do not change to Shardborne. \nIf a being is transformed into a Shardborne, the process is usually total; it is very rare for vestiges of the original being to remain, at least physically. Psychologically, some Shardborne can be considered a &lt;a href=\"Iscea\"&gt;separate persona&lt;/a&gt; from their pre-corrupted self, while &lt;a href=\"Elsauli\"&gt;others&lt;/a&gt; can be considered one and the same.\nShardborne are driven to kill by endless visions of terror, and the slightest exposure to Worldstone shards sends the Shardborne into a rabid craze. Despite this, Shardborne have displayed a modicum of intelligence; intentionally using Worldstone shards on creatures to create more Shardborne, for instance. References have been made to a \"chorus of voices\" that link the Shardborne, with some voices more dominant than others.\nShardborne appear to willingly seek out shardstorms.\nHistory.\n&lt;a href=\"Timeline%231265\"&gt;When&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Arreat\"&gt;Mount Arreat&lt;/a&gt; was sundered, the &lt;a href=\"Southern%20Dreadlands\"&gt;Southern Dreadlands&lt;/a&gt; was subjected to horrifying red storms that carried tiny splinters and particles of the destroyed Worldstone. When a storm passed through a settlement, it either cut the inhabitants to pieces or transformed them into Shardborne. \n&lt;a href=\"Timeline%231272\"&gt;Seven years later&lt;/a&gt;, the Shardborne were wielded by the &lt;a href=\"Cult%20of%20Terror\"&gt;Cult of Terror&lt;/a&gt;, who hoped to unleash the Shardborne on &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Albrecht\"&gt;Some&lt;/a&gt; were &lt;a href=\"undead\"&gt;reanimated dead&lt;/a&gt;, shaped into lethal attackers.\nIn-game.\nThe are a group of monsters in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". They were introduced in the &lt;a href=\"Dark%20Rebirth\"&gt;Dark Rebirth&lt;/a&gt; update, and also appear in &lt;a href=\"Splintered%20Souls\"&gt;Splintered Souls&lt;/a&gt; update. They appear in &lt;a href=\"Leoric%27s%20Manor\"&gt;Leoric's Manor&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Tristram%20Cathedral%20%28Dungeon%29\"&gt;Tristram Cathedral&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"dungeon\"&gt;dungeon&lt;/a&gt;, and in the Southern Dreadlands zone."}
